HEADWORD: Helot
<hw>He"lot</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Helotes</ets>, <ets>Hilotae</ets>, pl., fr. Gr. <grk>E'e`lws</grk>
and <grk>E'elw`ths</grk> a bondman or serf of the Spartans; so named
from <grk>'Elos</grk>, a town of Laconia, whose inhabitants were
enslaved; or perh. akin to <grk>e`lei^n</grk> to take, conquer, used as
2d aor. of <?/.]</ety> <def>A slave in ancient Sparta; a Spartan serf;
hence, a slave or serf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those unfortunates, the <qex>Helots</qex> of mankind, more or less
numerous in every community.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Helotism</ent>⟦br⟧
